Introduction

Text Mining and Natural Language Processing are two of the most interesting fields right now in Data Mining. Whether you are working with tweets from some controversial political candidate or going through thousands of pages of content to discover some kind of pattern, there’s a lot you can do right now with the algorithms and packages available in R (or Python, for that matter). Livros são mídias interessantes e desafiadoras para se trabalhar, já que são textos que carregam muitas vezes significados ocultos, ironias, floreios e vocabulário mais rebuscado do que conteúdos mais imediatistas e voltados à comunicação direta, como um artigo de notícias ou um tweet. For me, as a bookworm, one of the most interesting possibilities is to take one book and dissecting it, trabalhando principalmente no sentido de produzir visualizações, verificar quais são as palavras mais frequentes num livro e realizar testes estatísticos para, por exemplo, determinar relações entre as palavras.

No entanto, este processo não é simples nem straightforward. Alguns dos desafios normalmente encontrados: * Where to obtain the book * Manual transformations and inspecting the data as you go

Fontes: http://www.sthda.com/english/wiki/text-mining-and-word-cloud-fundamentals-in-r-5-simple-steps-you-should-know https://guilhermegarcia.github.io/lusiadas.html https://rpubs.com/tsholliger/301914

Transformações Carrie

docscarrie <- Corpus(VectorSource(carrie))
docscarrie <- docscarrie %>%
  tm_map(toSpace, "/") %>%
  tm_map(toSpace, "”") %>%
  tm_map(toSpace, "“") %>%
  tm_map(toSpace, "@") %>%
  tm_map(toSpace, "\\|") %>%
  tm_map(toSpace, "—") %>%
  tm_map(toSpace, "’") %>%
  tm_map(toSpace, "…")
inspect(docscarrie)
docscarrie <- docscarrie %>%
  tm_map(content_transformer(tolower)) %>%
  tm_map(removeNumbers) %>% # Remove numbers 
  tm_map(removeWords, stopen) %>% # Remove english common stopword 
  tm_map(removePunctuation) %>% # Remove punctuations 
  tm_map(stripWhitespace) # Eliminate extra white spaces
  #docs <- tm_map(docs, removeWords, c("”", "“"))  # Remove your own stop word
inspect(docscarrie)
tidy_carrie <- data.frame(text = sapply(docscarrie, as.character), stringsAsFactors = FALSE) %>% 
  mutate(paragraph = row_number()) %>% 
  ungroup()
tidy_carrie <- tidy_carrie %>%  unnest_tokens(input = text, output = word)
head(tidy_carrie,100)
carrie_trigrams <- tidy_carrie %>%
  unnest_tokens(trigram, text, token = "ngrams", n = 3) %>%
  tidyr::separate(trigram, c("word1", "word2", "word3"), sep = " ") %>%
  filter(!is.na(word1)) %>%
  count(word1, word2, word3, sort = TRUE)

carrie_trigrams %>%
  top_n(n = 10,wt = n) %>%
  tidyr::unite("word",word1,word2,word3,sep=" ") %>%
  mutate(word = reorder(word, n)) %>%
  ggplot(aes(n, word, fill=n)) +
  geom_col() +
  scale_fill_gradient(low="#EF3B2C",high="#CB181D")+
  labs(title = "Most frequent bigrams in 'Carrie'",y = "Bigrams",x="No. of times") +  geom_text(aes(label = n), hjust = -0.05, size = 4,
            position = position_dodge(0.5)) + theme(legend.position = "none",plot.title = element_text(hjust = 0.5))

Sentiment Analysis - comparação de 3 lexicons

afinn = tidy_carrie %>%
  inner_join(get_sentiments("afinn")) %>% 
  group_by(index = paragraph %/% 20) %>% 
  summarise(sentiment = sum(value)) %>% 
  mutate(method = "AFINN")
Joining, by = "word"
`summarise()` ungrouping output (override with `.groups` argument)
bing_and_nrc <- bind_rows(
  tidy_carrie %>% 
    inner_join(get_sentiments("bing")) %>%
    mutate(method = "Bing et al."),
  tidy_carrie %>% 
    inner_join(get_sentiments("nrc") %>%  filter(sentiment %in% c("positive","negative"))
    ) %>%
    mutate(method = "NRC")) %>%
  count(method, index = paragraph %/% 20, sentiment) %>%
  tidyr::spread(sentiment, n, fill = 0) %>%
  mutate(sentiment = positive - negative)
Joining, by = "word"
Joining, by = "word"
bind_rows(afinn, 
          bing_and_nrc) %>%
  ggplot(aes(index, sentiment, fill = method)) +
  geom_col(show.legend = FALSE) +
  facet_wrap(~method, ncol = 1, scales = "free_y")

bing_word_counts %>%
  group_by(sentiment) %>%
  top_n(10) %>%
  ungroup() %>%
  mutate(word = reorder(word, n)) %>%
  ggplot(aes(n, word, fill = sentiment)) +
  geom_col(show.legend = FALSE) +
  facet_wrap(~sentiment, scales = "free_y") +
  labs(x = "Contribution to sentiment",
       y = NULL)
